    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="760"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d760">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 815.51/327.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 105.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 27, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that the loan of
                    $500,000.00 negotiated by Mr. Samuel Zemurray on behalf of this Government with
                    the Whitney Central National Bank of New Orleans (my No. 85, of the 4th instant
                    and previous correspondence) was approved yesterday with the alterations
                    recommended by the Committee on Finance and Public Credit in its report on this
                    contract which goes to the Department as clipping No. 57 cut from <hi
                        rend="italic">El Nuevo Tiempo</hi>, No. 270, of to-day’s date.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d760fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The changes in the contract are significant. The more important affect Articles
                    IV and VI, altering the powers of the agent to be appointed by the bank to
                    administer the customs at Puerto Cortes in case of failure on the part of this
                    Government to make the payments to the bank and eliminating the restraints put
                    on this Government in the matter of tariff legislation.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles D. White</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
